    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b436e52a-101e-41e5-b1bf-facf7575e2f3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an 11-year-old girl who arrives for evaluation with constant motion in her limbs, quick shifts in attention, and a bright but restless presence. She swings her legs under the chair, interrupts with answers before questions are finished, and frequently looks around the room at sounds or movement in the hallway. Her clothes are clean but slightly mismatched, suggesting hurried mornings. She is friendly, talkative, and eager to please, yet it is difficult for her to stay seated or follow a long conversation without becoming distracted.\n\nAt school, {patientName} is described as imaginative, verbally strong, and socially enthusiastic, but she struggles to sustain focus on worksheets, complete multi-step instructions, and wait her turn. Teachers report fidgeting, blurting out, careless mistakes, and incomplete assignments despite clear understanding of the material when engaged one-to-one. She enjoys art, scooter riding, and gymnastics, and she can focus for long periods on activities she finds exciting, especially drawing characters and building elaborate stories with friends.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with her mother, father, and younger brother. Family life is caring but often strained by repeated reminders about homework, chores, and bedtime routines. She frequently forgets where she left school items, starts tasks without finishing them, and becomes emotionally frustrated when corrected repeatedly. Even so, she is affectionate, humorous, and has several close friends who appreciate her energy and creativity.\n\nHer lifestyle is active, with regular outdoor play and participation in an after-school gymnastics class twice weekly. Sleep is somewhat inconsistent because she resists settling down at night, and mornings can be chaotic due to distractibility. Diet is generally adequate, though she sometimes skips parts of breakfast when rushed. Her parents are concerned that her symptoms now interfere with school performance, family routines, and self-esteem, especially as she compares herself with classmates who seem better organized."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:b6741e3c-618c-4837-9ad4-31692ec6e092",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has had symptoms of inattention, excessive activity, and impulsivity since early primary school, with clear worsening of academic and behavioral impact over the last 2 years. There is no history of seizures, head trauma, intellectual disability, or autism spectrum diagnosis. She has never been psychiatrically hospitalized and has not previously received stimulant medication. Her pediatric history is otherwise unremarkable apart from a remote tonsillectomy in early childhood. Developmental milestones were achieved within expected ranges, although caregivers recall that she was unusually active even as a preschooler.\n\nShe sleeps about 8-9 hours nightly but has prolonged sleep onset on many evenings. Screen time often increases distractibility near bedtime. There is no substance exposure. She is physically active, attends school regularly, and has supportive parents who are engaged with behavioral strategies and teacher feedback. Current concerns include declining classroom performance, frequent redirection, emotional frustration, and low confidence related to repeated criticism for behaviors she seems unable to control consistently."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
